### .NET version

.NET 9 Preview 4

### Did it work in .NET Framework?

Yes

### Did it work in any of the earlier releases of .NET Core or .NET 5+?

_No response_

### Issue description

When an anchored (or docked) RichTextBox is resized due to the resizing of the parent control, the last column of pixels is sometimes not cleared / redrawn. It appears as if the previously rendered text remains.

![image](https://github.com/dotnet/winforms/assets/5320760/e677b82b-49a0-4047-ae7c-9fecaed7000a)

### Steps to reproduce

Create a new `Form`-Instance with the following constructor code:

```csharp
public Form1()
{
    // Text fits exactly
    Size = new Size(290, 150);

    var rtb = new RichTextBox()
    {
        BorderStyle = BorderStyle.None,
        Dock = DockStyle.Top,
        Font = new Font("Segoe UI", 12),
        ReadOnly = true,
        ScrollBars = RichTextBoxScrollBars.None,
        Text = "Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consetetur"
    };

    var btn = new Button()
    {
        Dock = DockStyle.Bottom,
        Text = "Resize"
    };

    btn.Click += (s, e) =>
    {
        // Reduce the size by 1px
        Size = new Size(Size.Width - 1, Size.Height);

        btn.Enabled = false;
    };

    Controls.Add(btn);
    Controls.Add(rtb);
}
```

Initial visialization => OK
Click the resize button once => NOK

![image](https://github.com/dotnet/winforms/assets/5320760/9dbb4252-abc7-4816-ac94-5bbe89fccd4c)

If I diff those two screenshots I get the following image (notice the unchanged tip of the letter "r" on the top right).
![image](https://github.com/dotnet/winforms/assets/5320760/f1b58284-a7e3-4588-8dce-ff631adbf1f9)

I am not sure why the letter "t" also changed, but that would be another issue.
